[1] Vorarlberg, cattle
Date: Fri 4 Mar 2016
Source: Agrar Heute (Germany) [in German, trans. Sabine Zentis, edited]
http://www.agrarheute.com/news/rindertuberkulose-33-betriebe-wurden-gesperrt


Bovine TB: 33 farms under restrictions
--------------------------------------
Several cases of bovine tuberculosis [bTB] have been detected in the Austrian Vorarlberg regions. 20 cows and calves had to be slaughtered and the test results for 100 more dairy cows are awaited.

TB was confirmed on 9 farms; one farm had all its stock slaughtered because one animal had open lesions. A further 24 holdings are under restriction as contacts. The animals shared pasture with the infected animals and are now awaiting a 2nd test.

Infection is from animal to animal, and the bacterium can be transmitted through inhalation or contaminated water or feed.

The highest risk for humans is milk from infected animals. Mycobacteria are killed by pasteurisation. It can take years for an infected individual to show symptoms, like coughing or emaciation.

Infection can occur between humans and animals and vice versa. _Mycobacterium bovis_, the causative agent of cattle TB, occurs in cattle worldwide.

In Europe, the incidence of disease has currently increased in Spain, Ireland, Great Britain and Northern Ireland, according to the German Federal Ministry.

Many countries are free from bTB, which means that, according to the EU definition, at least 99.9 percent of the cattle farms of a country are free from TB. Germany is considered free of tuberculosis. Nevertheless, according to FLI, the Federal Research Institute for Animal Health, on a few holdings animals are found to be infected.

