[_Mycobacterium caprae_ has been identified during recent years in Austrian and German cattle in the alpine region.

According to Austria's semi-annual reports to the OIE since 2013, the following bTB cases have been reported; all within the Alpine region (Tirol and Vorarlberg provinces):
2013: Tirol (2 in February, 1 in October). Vorarlberg (2 in February). Total 5 cases.
2014: Tirol (1 in January, 2 in February). Vorarlberg (6 in February, 1 in March). Total 10.
2015: Tirol (1 in March). Vorarlberg (2 in February, 1 in March). Total 4.

According to Germany's semi-annual reports for the same period:
2013: April (1), May (2), June (1); total 4, locations not given.
2014: February (1, Niedersachsen), May (1, Saarland); total 2.
2015: February (2), April (1); total 3, locations not given.

Additional diagnosed cases in German bovines, referring to both _M. tuberculosis_ and _M. caprae_, are presented in the reports of the German Federal Research Institute for Animal Health (FLI); http://tsis.fli.bund.de/Reports/Info_SO.aspx?ts=204 (in German).

As indicated in the commentary of posting 20130317.1590824 (2013), "the role of wildlife as bTB reservoirs has become a matter of discussion between farmers and the organized hunters. During the winter months, red deer are kept and fed in enclosures. This leads to rather crowded conditions and a massive increase in the deer population and to weaker deer (infected with TB?) since animals which would otherwise die somewhere in the Alps during the winter, are kept alive and might become an ongoing source of infection. One of the sites suspected to enhance infection are the mentioned enclosures, where sometimes young cattle are housed for several days to become adapted to the Alps."

The above comment is in line with the results of a study in the Alpine Region by a team composed of Austrian, German, Italian and Swiss researchers (Ref 1; thanks to Sabine Zentis), from which the abstract and conclusions are presented.

1. Abstract
"To estimate the prevalence of bovine tuberculosis in the Alpine region, we studied the epidemiology of _Mycobacterium caprae_ in wildlife during the 2009-2012 hunting seasons. Free-ranging red deer (_Cervus elaphus_) were a maintenance host in a hot-spot area, mainly located in Austria."

2. The authors concluded (references omitted):
"Supplementary feeding is common in the hotspot area to prevent migration and to keep red deer populations high. In the hot-spot area, the overall density is 5.6 animals/sq km but because of aggregation, which is considered the main cause of bovine tuberculosis maintenance in wildlife, winter habitats of red deer around feeding sites have up to 46.2 animals/sq km km2. Low (0.5-2.5 and 2-4/sq km) or medium densities (9.7 deer/sq km) with prevalence estimates of 0 percent were found in Switzerland. Brescia, the only place in Italy where _M. caprae_ was found in red deer, is considered a high-density region (16 animals/sq km), but management strategies promoting aggregation are largely absent in Italy and Switzerland. Furthermore, red deer in the hot-spot area are a reservoir for bovine tuberculosis and are the source of _M. caprae_ infections for domestic cattle grazing on Alpine pastures during the summer. Molecular-epidemiologic studies indicate that _M. caprae_ isolates from red deer and cattle are of the same genotype.

"Our finding that retropharyngeal lymph nodes and mesenteric lymph nodes were often the primary site of infection suggests oral rather than aerosol transmission. Oral transmission does not require direct contact, either among red deer or between red deer and cattle."

According to chapter 2.4.7 ("Bovine tuberculosis") of OIE's Manual of Diagnostic Tests and Vaccines for Terrestrial Animals (updated 2009), _M. caprae_ is "known to be zoonotic. In central Europe, _M. caprae_ has been identified as a common cause of bovine tuberculosis. Disease caused by _M. caprae_ is not considered to be substantially different from that caused by _M. bovis_ and the same tests can be used for its diagnosis" (see http://www.oie.int/fileadmin/Home/eng/Health_standards/tahm/2.04.07_BOVINE_TB.pdf).

The national and international consequences of the described situation are a matter for clarification (comment in 20130317.1590824).

References:
1. M Fink, C Schleicher, M Gonano et al. (2015). Red Deer as Maintenance Host for Bovine Tuberculosis, Alpine Region. Emerging Infectious Diseases 21 (3), 464-467. http://wwwnc.cdc.gov/eid/article/21/3/pdfs/14-1119.pdf
2. Prodinger W.M., Brandstatter A., Naumann L. et al (2005). Characterization of _Mycobacterium caprae_ isolates from Europe by mycobacterial interspersed repetitive unit genotyping. J. Clin. Microbiol., 43, 4984-4992.
- Mod.AS

